    </equation><para id="import-auto-id1846608">Here <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>tot</m:mtext><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo>

</m:mrow>
<m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>tot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mtext>sin 110º</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{"tot"y} } =v rSub { size 8{"tot"} }  = v rSub { size 8{"tot"} }  "sin 110º"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>; thus,</para><equation id="eip-206"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>w</m:mtext><m:mi fontstyle="italic">y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mtext>38</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0 m/s</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>940</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mtext>45</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0 m/s</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mn>9</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>29 m/s.</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{wy} } = \( "38" "." 0" m/s" \)  \( 0 "." "940" \)  - "45" "." 0" m/s"= - 9 "." "29"" m/s."} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation><para id="import-auto-id1923978">This minus sign indicates motion south which is consistent with the diagram.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1915356">Now that the perpendicular components of the wind velocity <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>w</m:mtext><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{wx} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>w</m:mtext><m:mi>y</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{wy} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> are known, we can find the magnitude and direction of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">v</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>w</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{v rSub { size 8{w} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. First, the magnitude is</para><equation id="eip-128"><m:math>
        <m:semantics>
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mrow>
